<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96994069228486></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96994069228486><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/strategy/classes.html?class=4&mid=96994069228486>RE: Creating a Bard</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?id=1597><span id= >Rezn</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>12 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Sep 25th 11:58 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I personally believe Half Elves are the best race for bards.  We have the highest dexterity of the three races possible, our charisma is the same as the other two as well.  We possess higher than average agility (Not as high as a wood elf, but not as low as a human), and decent strength and stamina (Not as high as a human, but not as low as a wood elf).  Plus, we recieve infravision, unlike our human ancestors.  Our wisdom stat is low, which is good for us bards after all, since that is the one statistic that doesn't apply to us at all!  For the other two races, their inniate statistic points are wasted on wisdom being higher than average (Or just average, for humans).  The one and only thing Half Elves lack is the Wood Elf's inniate ability to hide and forage (Though we get those ourselves later on) and the ability to wear small and large armor, which won't really affect you past your 10th level IMHO.<br><br>As for statistics, I say try to even out your 25 points in Dexterity and Charisma ONLY!  And don't neglect charisma, its one of our most vital statistics.  It's nice to stick in an extra five points or so into strength, sure.  But that will only help you past the first few levels.  I say ignore all other stats and just up your two most important ones.  You'll get plenty of jewelry/armor that will do that for you later on.<br><br>When you start out, I think you should stick one point into singing and the other four into One-handed slashing for a little boost to help you out.  The rest is simple, when you get advanced enough for the other skills just stick one and only one point into them, they will grow on their own without any problems.<br><br>As for the matter with dieties... the choice is up to you.  If you choose Agnostic, you can probably do any quest in the game with your Dark Elf/Iksar mask(s) and our Alliance Song.  Though I personally chose Veeshan, since the Bard is the only class that can choose the mighty Wyrm Queen as their diety, so there must be some reason for it!  Just as a note, practically everyone hates you if you choose Veeshan, except for maybe your guild.  So if you are new and don't need the troubles of faction bothering you, just pick Agnostic or perhaps Tunare.  It should work out well enough.<br><br>Damn... there MUST be a reason for bards to pick Veeshan... who knows, maybe I can walk through Veeshan's Peak later on if I get my Ring of Scale faction up high enough =)<br>&nbsp;<br>Ensis Arament</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
